=\"#zDocsTopicActionsMobile\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_main_5832477\" data-toggle=\"modal\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Jan 17, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104yye1705472567076.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/yye1705472567076.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/yye1705472567076.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"ngo1665702751259\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n                       \n Application Shells for Desktop Applications\n   </h1>\n<div class=\"body conbody\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">An application shell is the first object that is executed when a Windows or character mode application is started. It determines how the application is initialized and the first form component that is displayed.\n </p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__p_d12452e1_d12453e1_d12454e1\">The application shell runs the form components, and the menus, toolbars, and panels that may be associated with the application and its forms. It invokes the ProcScript in the apStart trigger and displays the initial form and a message line in which application messages are displayed.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__p_d12455e1_d12456e1_d12457e1\">Application shell triggers can be used to define behavior for setting up the application environment, authenticating users, executing components, and cleanup operations. An application shell can have an associated library containing messages, global ProcScripts, menus, and other applicable global objects.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__p_d12458e1_d12459e1_d12460e1\">Uniface has two types of shell for desktop applications:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__li_d5717e1_d5718e1_d5719e1\">For Windows applications, the shell properties control the appearance of the application window, such as background color or image, title bar text, and so on. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"dig1705473594272.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/dig1705473594272.html\" title=\"Create a Windows shell for Uniface applications that run on any supported Windows platform.\">Define a Windows Application Shell</a>.\n                        </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__li_d5720e1_d5721e1_d5722e1\">For character mode applications, the shell enables you to define the layout and behavior. The appearance is determined by text colors and video attributes, which can be set in configuration files. For more information, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"apf1705474154305.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/apf1705474154305.html\" title=\"Create a shell for Uniface applications that run in character mode on any supported platform, such as Unix or Linux.\">Define a Character Mode Application Shell</a>.\n                        </li>\n</ul>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__section_vdk_jzz_c1c\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d206124e83\">Properties of Application Shells</h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__p_d12464e1_d12465e1_d12466e1\">Both Windows and character mode application shells\n        support the following properties:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__ul_cbm_lzz_c1c\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__li_d5723e1_d5724e1_d5725e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"myt1665702689407.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/myt1665702689407.html\" title=\"Title displayed in the window title bar or browser tab when the application shell, form, or server page is run. If no title is specified, the object name is displayed.\">Title</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__li_d5726e1_d5727e1_d5728e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"wyl1665702688770.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/wyl1665702688770.html\" title=\"Specifies the library containing the global objects used by the component or application shell. If no library is specified, the library defined for the application shell is used. Otherwise, SYSTEM_LIBRARY is used as the default.\">Library</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__li_d5729e1_d5730e1_d5731e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"glg1665702714695.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/glg1665702714695.html\" title=\"Name of the menu bar initially displayed for the current form or application shell.\">Menu Bar</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__li_d5732e1_d5733e1_d5734e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"nnt1665702586853.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/nnt1665702586853.html\" title=\"Name of the pop-up menu object to display when the user clicks the mouse button in this component, entity, or field.\">Pop-up Menu</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__li_d5735e1_d5736e1_d5737e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"xtq1665702714794.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/xtq1665702714794.html\" title=\"This property specifies the name of the panel that is displayed with the form or application shell at runtime.\">Panel</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__li_d5738e1_d5739e1_d5740e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"oat1665702714863.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/oat1665702714863.html\" title=\"Specifies a panel that is available for the duration of the application session, even if a panel has been specified for the current component, or a toolbar definition exists.\">Session Panel</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"ngo1665702751259__li_d5741e1_d5742e1_d5743e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"txw1665702714934.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/txw1665702714934.html\" title=\"Position of the panel for a form or application shell when displayed at runtime.\">Panel Position</a>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</section>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div><div class=\"contentPlaceholder\" style=\"height: 500px;\"><div class=\"contentContainer zDocsSideBoxes\"><div><h5 aria-level=\"5\" class=\"css-g931ng\">Related Links</h5><ul><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/shh1665702750613.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Developing Desktop Applications</a><p>Enterprise desktop applications are distributed client/server applications—they allow users to retrieve and maintain data in a remote database using a locally-run application. Desktop applications are usually highly interactive, and provide a much faster response time than most web applications.</p></li><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/dig1705473594272.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Define a Windows Application Shell</a><p>Create a Windows shell for Uniface applications that run on any supported Windows platform.</p></li><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/apf1705474154305.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Define a Character Mode Application Shell</a><p>Create a shell for Uniface applications that run in character mode on any supported platform, such as Unix or Linux.</p></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_5832477\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_5832477\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Application Shells for Desktop Applications Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Jan 17, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Application Shells for Desktop Applications An application shell is the first object that is executed when a Windows or character mode application is started. It determines how the application is initialized and the first form component that is displayed. The application shell runs the form components, and the menus, toolbars, and panels that may be associated with the application and its forms. It invokes the ProcScript in the apStart trigger and displays the initial form and a message line in which application messages are displayed. Application shell triggers can be used to define behavior for setting up the application environment, authenticating users, executing components, and cleanup operations. An application shell can have an associated library containing messages, global ProcScripts, menus, and other applicable global objects. Uniface has two types of shell for desktop applications: For Windows applications, the shell properties control the appearance of the application window, such as background color or image, title bar text, and so on. For more information, see Define a Windows Application Shell . For character mode applications, the shell enables you to define the layout and behavior. The appearance is determined by text colors and video attributes, which can be set in configuration files. For more information, see Define a Character Mode Application Shell . Properties of Application Shells Both Windows and character mode application shells support the following properties: Title Library Menu Bar Pop-up Menu Panel Session Panel Panel Position Related Links Developing Desktop Applications Enterprise desktop applications are distributed client/server applications—they allow users to retrieve and maintain data in a remote database using a locally-run application. Desktop applications are usually highly interactive, and provide a much faster response time than most web applications. Define a Windows Application Shell Create a Windows shell for Uniface applications that run on any supported Windows platform. Define a Character Mode Application Shell Create a shell for Uniface applications that run in character mode on any supported platform, such as Unix or Linux. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}